A
gyro-stabilized
platform
system
,
using
restrained
gyros
,
is
well
suited
for
automatic
leveling
because
of
the
characteristics
of
the
gyro-platform-servo
combination
.

The
platform
angle
**yf
is
the
angle
about
which
the
gyro
is
controlling
.

i.e.
,
high
loop
gain
causes
the
system
to
respond
to
horizontal
components
of
accelerations
.

It
must
be
noticed
in
Fig.
7-1
that
the
accelerometer
responds
to
any
input
acceleration
.

When
the
system
is
arranged
for
automatic
leveling
,
the
platform
angles
respond
to
any
horizontal
components
of
acceleration
acting
on
the
accelerometers
.

The
amplifier
is
designed
so
that
its
gain
is
large
for
accelerometer
signals
above
a
certain
threshold
level
.

The
effect
is
that
the
platform
returns
from
an
off-level
position
at
a
rapid
rate
until
it
is
nearly
level
,
at
which
point
the
platform
is
controlled
by
a
proportional
servo
with
low
enough
frequency
response
so
that
the
noise
has
little
effect
on
the
leveling
process
.

The
automatic
leveling
system
described
in
this
section
is
readily
adaptable
to
a
gyro-stabilized
platform
consisting
of
three
integrating
gyros
.

This
leveling
system
will
hold
the
platform
on-level
,
automatically
,
as
long
as
the
system
is
actuated
.

Manual
leveling
requires
an
appropriate
display
of
the
accelerometer
outputs
.

However
,
skill
is
required
on
the
part
of
an
operator
to
level
a
platform
to
any
degree
of
accuracy
.

Also
,
it
requires
more
time
as
compared
to
the
automatic
approach
.

Platform
heading
consists
of
orienting
the
sensitive
axis
of
the
accelerometers
parallel
to
the
desired
coordinate
system
of
the
navigator
.

For
purely
inertial
navigators
,
two
techniques
are
available
to
accomplish
the
platform
heading
:
Use
of
external
or
surveying
equipment
to
establish
proper
heading
;
;

The
sighting
procedure
includes
the
use
of
a
fixture
for
the
transit
to
project
a
beam
of
light
,
which
is
darkened
by
crossed
hairs
,
on
the
accelerometer
mirror
